snippet.textDisplay: Call me crazy, but the show would seriously help itself by writing out Archie altogether. Whether he gets put on a bus or even killed off, he’s the weakest link the show has. The character I mean, not KJ Apa. When he’s given good writing, which usually happens when Fred’s life is at risk or being remembered, KJ Apa can really pull out an affecting performance. However the average quality of the Archie writing is low quality. He usually gets paired up going against Hiram, another character the show has long outgrown. Despite a number of attempts by the writers, trying to incorporate Archie into the main plot has never really worked convincingly unless it’s involved Hiram. Season 1 he had his music vs football, the horribly written Grundy storyline and temporary romance with Valerie. Season two onwards it’s entirely downhill. The fact the Archie’s uncle storyline went nowhere proves that the show doesn’t know how to use him except for eye candy. You know that Simpsons gag where Marge can get all the curlers in her hair in the time it takes Homer to list all the jobs he’s had up to that point? You could do the same gag with roles Archie has played in the plot that had meaningful development to his character.

snippet.textDisplay: One of the worst parts about introducing a secret relative into a narrative that I see writers do time and time again is leaving explanation of these relatives' past to your characters dialogue (i.e. Archie's Mom's exposition scene about Frank?) versus showing a brief scene of the relatives past. Like wouldn't a scene between young Fred and Frank (are those the names, I don't watch this show like I used to) with the DUI debacle be interesting?? Same with the Clifford twins. I understand shows may not have the resources for those extra actors or time in their scripts but then that begs the question of why even add these secret relatives in the first place if you won't flesh them out at the most microscopic level??
